<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900905-0035</DOCNO><DOCID>900905-0035.</DOCID><HL>   McDonnell Douglas   Wins Pact to Build   40 Jets for Kuwait</HL><DATE>09/05/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16</SO><CO>   MD MDEST BA PC</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- McDonnell Douglas Corp. won a $140 millioncontract to build 40 F/A-18 Hornet jet aircraft for thegovernment of Kuwait, the Defense Department said.   The contract covers equipment purchases that were workedout several years ago under the foreign military salesprogram, the Pentagon said. But the agreement was justrecently signed with Kuwait's exiled government, which fledthe country after the Aug. 2 invasion by Iraq.</LP><TEXT>   The sale is proceeding because &quot;the government of Kuwaitstill exists,&quot; and the U.S. hopes the exiled government willregain its territory from Iraq, a Pentagon spokesman said.   The F/A-18 performs both fighter and attack roles. Thecontract, which is to be completed in September 1993,involves two versions of the aircraft, 32 F/A-18Cs and eightF/A-18Ds.   A separate contract, also being awarded to McDonnellDouglas, covers a $5.4 million order for technicalpublications for the Kuwaiti F/A-18s.                                                                                                          In other Pentagon awards, Vitro Services Corp. got a $34.5million Army contract for operation of the development testcenter range.                                                                                                          Charles Stark Draper Laboratories Inc. won a $29.5 millionAir Force contract for missile technical support.                                                                                                          Boeing Co. received an $18.3 million Air Force contractfor radio sets.                                                                                                          Ocean Line of Azores Inc. was issued a $13.1 million Navycontract for cargo transport.</TEXT></DOC>